PARAGRAPH.#text: XL Group PLC's XL board increased the property-and-casualty insurer's quarterly dividend by 27% and approved a new, $850 million stock-repurchase program. The company earlier said that roughly 60% of the estimated losses were related to its reinsurance unit. Within the reinsurance business, XL Group said about 20% of the estimated losses are at its marine segment, with the remainder related to property reinsurance.

Headlines.Headline: XL Group 3Q Earnings Drop On Catastrophe Losses

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES XL Group PLC XL third-quarter earnings fell 45%, as the property-and-casualty insurer's core profit also dropped on another quarter of heavy catastrophe losses. The company, which also provides reinsurance, has continued to report higher premiums, even as losses from disasters pushed it into the red in the first quarter. While catastrophe losses this year have been particularly harsh for the insurance industry, XL's hit from disasters had been relatively light. In the latest period, its combined ratio--the percentage of premiums paid out on losses and expenses--deteriorated to 101.6% from 94.9% in the P&C business.

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES XL Group PLC XL second-quarter profit rose 16% on lower taxes and more income from affiliates, while core earnings at the property-and-casualty insurer unexpectedly rose thanks to a relatively light hit from natural disasters. The company, which also provides reinsurance, said combined ratio -- the percentage of premiums paid out on losses and expenses -- deteriorated slightly to 94.9% from 92.2% in the P&C business. Catastrophe losses in the division jumped to $68.3 million from $16.8 million.

Headlines.Author: John Kell
Headlines.Headline: XL Group Sees $50 Million To $75 Million In Losses Tied To US Disasters

PARAGRAPH.#text: XL Group PLC XL estimated net losses related to storms in the midwestern and southeastern U.S., including devastating tornados, would total $50 million to $75 million. The property and casualty insurer's estimate was pretax and net of reinsurance and reinstatement premiums, with the majority attributable to XL Group's reinsurance segment. The company, which also provides reinsurance, and its peers have been stung for over a year by a number of losses that occurred in New Zealand and Australia, as well as a huge earthquake in Chile and an earthquake and tsunami and Japan.

Headlines.Author: Joan E. Solsman
Headlines.Headline: XL Group Swings To Red In 1Q On Wide Catastrophe Losses

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES XL Group PLC XL swung to a first-quarter loss on wide catastrophe losses from recent natural disasters, and the property and casualty insurer's core loss was deeper than expected. The company, which also provides reinsurance, reported natural catastrophe losses of $387.4 million, net of reinstatement premiums, in its property and casualty operations. The company last month estimated its total losses from March's devastating earthquake and tsunami in Japan would range from $190 million to $290 million, on top of an estimated $70 million to $85 million in losses it already anticipated from a New Zealand earthquake.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: XL Group Swings To Red In 1Q On Wide Catastrophe Losses

Headlines.Author: Kathy Shwiff
Headlines.Headline: XL Group 3Q Profit Jumps; Core Earnings Miss Estimates

PARAGRAPH.#text: XL Group PLC's XL third-quarter profit soared on smaller investment losses, gains related to changes in currency values and hedging impacts. But core earnings slumped as net premiums fell, and the property-and-casualty insurer's profit fell short of Wall Street's expectations. The company, which has a market capitalization of about $7.2 billion, also said it plans to repurchase $1 billion in shares. Since June 30, it has bought $375.4 million. Chief Executive Mike McGavick pointed out the company's "solid underwriting discipline," but said it continues to "feel the impact that the prolonged soft market has on earnings.
